Background

This analysis concerns a database of houses sold in Ames, Iowa, including various informations on the properties. The objective is to build a robust and accurate predictive model of the selling price, so that real estate investors will be able to identify undervalued or overvalued properties and neighborhoods and make data-informed choices.

Training Data and relevant packages

In order to better assess the quality of the model we will produce, the data have been randomly divided into three separate pieces: a training data set, a testing data set, and a validation data set. For now we will load the training data set, the others will be loaded and used later.

load("ames_train.Rdata")

The following packages are used throughout the data analysis.

library(statsr)
library(dplyr)
library(BAS)
library(ggplot2)
library(MASS)

Part 1 - Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Exploratory Data Analysis allows for a preliminary understanding of the relationship between the different variables and a selection of the most important features that will be included in the multiple linear regression.

The database contains sales of houses built between 1872 and 2010. It is interesting to see how these properties are distributed by age at the time of the survey, as in the following plot.

# type your code for Question 1 here, and Knit
ggplot(ames_train,aes(x=2010 - Year.Built)) + 
    stat_bin(bins = 30) + ylim(c(0, 135)) +  
    stat_bin(bins=30, geom="text", aes(label=..count..), vjust=-1.5) + labs(title = "Distribution of properties by age at the time of the survey", x = 'Age', y = 'Count') +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 80))

It appears that the age distribution is strongly right-skewed, with a large number of new houses, and multi-modal. In fact, it appears there have been two periods of intensive house-building: one at the beginning of the 21st century and another earlier between the Fifties and the Seventies.

For the purpose of building a linear model of price, we assume that all observations in the database are generated from the same process. Therefore, we need check if the distribution of price depends on the various sale conditions listed under the Sale.Condition variable.

ggplot(data = ames_train, mapping = aes(x = Sale.Condition, y = price)) + geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()

The range of prices is clearly affected by the sale condition. Sale conditions other than Normal generate prices that do not reflect the actual market value of a property, therefore the corresponding data may be discarded. The following code calculates the percentage of data that would be kept after the exclusion of houses sold in conditions other than normal.

ames_train_normal <- subset(ames_train, Sale.Condition == 'Normal')
dim(ames_train_normal)[1]/dim(ames_train)[1]*100
## [1] 83.4

This is still a reasonable amount of data, therefore we will proceed with the selection of all properties sold in normal conditions.

ames_train <- ames_train %>%
  filter(Sale.Condition == "Normal")

The next scatter plot shows the linear relationship of log(price) to log(area), highlighted by the linear regression line in blue, surrounded by the confidence interval of the mean predicted log(price) for any given log(area). The points are colored by the Overall Quality score of the property, showing that the price increases proportionally to this variable as well.

ggplot(data = ames_train, mapping = aes(x = log(area), y = log(price), color = Overall.Qual)) + geom_point() + scale_color_gradient(low="blue", high="red")  + geom_smooth(method='lm')

Part 2 - Development and assessment of an initial model, following a semi-guided process of analysis

Section 2.1 An Initial Model

In order to get a better insight into this database, an initial simplified model will be generated in the frame of frequentist multiple linear regression. In this case, we have selected seven variables from the database which, according to our knowledge of the house market, are most likely to influence the price of a property. These are the inhabitable area, the area of the lot, the number of bedrooms above ground the overall quality score of the property, the quality score of the external part, the year in which the house was remodeled (0 if it was never remodeled), the presence of a central air conditioning system and the slope of the property (gentle, moderate or severe).

ames_reduced <- dplyr::select(ames_train, 'price', 'area', 'Lot.Area',
                              'Bedroom.AbvGr', 'Overall.Qual', 'Exter.Qual', 'Year.Remod.Add', 'Central.Air', 'Land.Slope')

n <- nrow(na.omit(ames_reduced))
m.init <- lm(log(price) ~ log(area) + log(Lot.Area) + 
               Bedroom.AbvGr + Overall.Qual + Exter.Qual + Year.Remod.Add + Central.Air + Land.Slope, data = na.omit(ames_reduced))

As can be seen from the previous summary of the multivariate linear model, all coefficients have a very low probability of being null, except of the variable representing the land slope. Also, the adjusted \(R^2\) score of the model, which represents the fraction of the variation of \(log(price)\) accounted for by the variation of the explanatory variables, is equal to 0.8634, which is a very satisfactory result.

The BIC method is known to produce more parsimonious models, especially for large databases. In this case, the variable Land.Slope has been dropped. The model resulting from the BIC is preferred because it uses less explanatory variables and is still capable of accounting for \(86\%\) of the variation of log(price).

Section 2.3 Initial Model Residuals

The performance of this initial BIC model is assessed by plotting the residuals versus the predicted values. For better understanding, the data are converted in Dollar units.

# Extract Predictions
predict.init <- exp(predict(m.init.BIC, ames_reduced))

# Extract Residuals
resid.init <- ames_reduced$price - predict.init

ggplot(mapping = aes(x = predict.init, y = resid.init)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm') + labs(x = 'Predictions under BIC', y = 'Residuals')

It can be seen that the average of the residuals tends to diverge from the expected value of zero for increasing predicted price. Next, we normalize the residuals by their average and standard deviation and generate a quantile-quantile plot.

# Normalize residuals
mu_resid <- mean(resid.init)
sd_resid <- sd(resid.init)
std_resid.init <- (resid.init - mu_resid)/sd_resid

# Normal Q-Q plot
qqnorm(std_resid.init, lty = 2)
qqline(std_resid.init)

It can be seen that the residuals that are more than two standard deviations away from the average diverge from the expected normal distribution. The previous two plots suggest that the linear regression approach that has been taken in this initial attempt needs some improvement in order to fulfill the assumptions of a linear model.

Section 2.4 Initial Model RMSE

A metric of the model performance is the root mean squared error (RMSE), which corresponds the square root of the mean of the squared residuals. The unit of the following result is dollars, consistently with the previous residual plots.

# Calculate RMSE
rmse.init <- sqrt(mean(resid.init^2))
rmse.init
## [1] 25576.77

Section 2.5 Overfitting

The initial model has been trained, and therefore optimized, on a given database. In order to evaluate the performance of this model on different data, we load a test database.

load("ames_test.Rdata")
ames_test <- ames_test %>%
  filter(Sale.Condition == "Normal")

The out-of-sample performance of the initial BIC model is evaluated by means of the RMSE criterion applied to the test database.

# Extract Predictions
predict.init.test <- exp(predict(m.init.BIC, ames_test))

# Extract Residuals
resid.init.test <- ames_test$price - predict.init.test

# Calculate RMSE
rmse.init.test <- sqrt(mean(resid.init^2))
rmse.init.test
## [1] 25576.77

As can be seen, the RMSE error is the same as with the training database, a fact that suggest that there is not much margin for improvement of the current model. The second evaluation metric is called coverage probability. If assumptions of the linear regression are met, a \(95\%\) predicted confidence interval for price should include the true value of price roughly \(95\%\) of the time. Let us verify this with the following code.

# Predict prices
predict.int <- exp(predict(m.init.BIC, ames_test, interval = "prediction"))

# Calculate proportion of observations that fall within prediction intervals
coverage.prob.int <- mean(ames_test$price > predict.int[,"lwr"] &
                            ames_test$price < predict.int[,"upr"])
coverage.prob.int
## [1] 0.9534884

So the condition of coverage probability is verified.

Part 3 - Development of a Final Model

The final multiple linear regression model involves a higher number of candidate predictors and is developed in a Bayesian framework. Given that there are \(16\) candidate explanatory variables, there are \(2^{16} = 65536\) possible linear models of log(price). The bas.lm function - Bayesian Adaptive Sampling (BAS) for Bayesian Model Averaging and Variable Selection in Linear Models - available in the BAS package allows to explore the space of possible multiple linear regression models. In the following application of the BAS algorithm, each model is assigned a uniform prior probability equal to \(1/2^{16}\). This is called a non-informative prior, which is used as a starting point in absence of more detailed information. The prior distribution for regression coefficients corresponds to the Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC), which includes a penalty function directly proportional to the number of regression parameters.

Section 3.1 Final Model

The following code applies the BAS algorithm and outputs its results with the summary function.

model.bas <- bas.lm(log(price) ~ Overall.Qual + log(Garage.Area + 1) +   
                  log(Total.Bsmt.SF + 1) + Garage.Cars + log(area) + 
                  Full.Bath + Half.Bath + 
                  Bedroom.AbvGr + Year.Built + Year.Remod.Add + log(X1st.Flr.SF) + 
                  log(X2nd.Flr.SF + 1) + log(Pool.Area + 1) +
                  log(Lot.Area) +  Central.Air + Overall.Cond,
                 data = ames_train, prior = "AIC", modelprior=uniform())

summary(model.bas)

The first column of the previous table corresponds to the posterior inclusion probability of each model coefficient given the training data set, \(P(B \neq 0\, |\, Y)\). The following columns correspond to the first five linear regression models with highest posterior probability (PostProbs) in descending order. The zeros and ones indicate if a variable is present in the model or not. Other values tabulated for each model are the Bayes factor (BF) of the model with respect to the Highest Probability Model (HPM), the R-squared (R2) in the ordinary least squares sense, the number of variables (dim) and the log of marginal likelihood (logmarg). It can be noticed that the first five models all have \(R^2\) around \(90\%\), which is an improvement with respect to the initial linear regression model obtained with the classical frequentist approach.

The posterior inclusion probabilities (PIP) of the explanatory variables are plotted below. The values above \(50\%\) are highlighted in blue.

par(mar=c(8,4,2,2))  
plot(model.bas, which = 4, ask = F, caption = "", sub.caption = "", col.in = "blue", col.ex = "darkgrey", lwd = 3)

It can be noticed that most of the candidate explanatory variables actually have a PIP higher than \(50\%\). Model uncertainty can also be visualized in the following plot. The y-axis contains all the predictors and the intercept, whereas the x-axis represents to the logarithm of the posterior odds of each model: since we used a uniform model prior, this corresponds to the logarithm of the Bayes factor. The columns correspond to the 17 models with higher posterior probability. The cells colored in black indicate that the corresponding predictor is not included in the model.

image(model.bas, rotate = FALSE)

Section 3.2 Transformation

Following the EDA, we decided to work on the prediction of the natural logarithm of price, taking the natural logarithm of all variables representing areas as well. In case one area-related variable can take the zero value, the variable is transformed adding “1” because the logarithm of zero is minus infinity.

Section 3.3 Variable Interaction

No variable interactions have been included in the final model. It will be shown a posteriori that this choice provides acceptable results.

Section 3.4 Variable Selection

The variables included in the final model were selected after we familiarized ourselves with the training database by means of the EDA and by building an initial simplified linear model. The choice was also aided by a certain degree of knowledge of the market and of the factors that influence the demand of properties.

Section 3.5 Model Testing

The selection of the final model among those produced by the BAS algorithm is made by calculating their respective Root Mean Squared Errors (RMSE) with reference to the ames_test database (the values will be in Dollars). The possible choices are the Highest Probability Model (HPM), which corresponds to the first column of the previous summary table, the BMA, which is an average of all models weighted by their posterior probabilities, and the Best Predictive Model (BPM), which is the single model the predictions of which are closest to those of the BMA. In principle, one can also use the Median Probability Model (MPM), which includes all predictors whose marginal posterior inclusion probabilities are greater than 0.5. In this particular case, however, the MPM is equal to the BPM.

pred.test.HPM <- predict(model.bas, newdata = ames_test, estimator="HPM")
pred.HPM.rmse <- sqrt(mean((exp(pred.test.HPM$fit) - ames_test$price)^2))
pred.HPM.rmse
## [1] 24556.14
pred.test.BPM <- predict(model.bas, newdata = ames_test, estimator="BPM")
pred.BPM.rmse <- sqrt(mean((exp(pred.test.BPM$fit) - ames_test$price)^2))
pred.BPM.rmse
## [1] 24573.38
pred.test.BMA <- predict(model.bas, newdata = ames_test, estimator="BMA", prediction=TRUE, se.fit=TRUE)
pred.BMA.rmse <- sqrt(mean((exp(pred.test.BMA$fit) - ames_test$price)^2))
pred.BMA.rmse
## [1] 24455.5

It can be seen that the BMA model has the lowest RMSE calculated on out-of-sample data and is therefore retained for the final evaluation.

Part 4 - Final Model Assessment

Section 4.1 Final Model Residual

In this section, the residuals of the predictions obtaines by applying the BMA model to the ames_test data set are presented. We will compare the residuals obtained on the complete range of predicted values with a subset of the residuals corresponding to a reduced range of predicted values.

Full range of predicted values

The first residuals vs predicted values plot shows that the quality of the prediction worsens for predicted values above 300k$, with the average residual tending to be below zero.

pred.test.BMA.resid <- exp(pred.test.BMA$fit) - ames_test$price
ggplot(mapping = aes(x = exp(pred.test.BMA$fit) , y = pred.test.BMA.resid )) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm') + labs(x = 'Predictions under BMA', y = 'Residuals')

As can be seen in the following plot, the residuals with strongly negative values tend to diverge from a normal distribution around the zero mean.

# Normalize residuals
mu_resid <- mean(pred.test.BMA.resid)
sd_resid <- sd(pred.test.BMA.resid)
std_resid.test <- (pred.test.BMA.resid - mu_resid)/sd_resid

# Normal Q-Q plot
qqnorm(std_resid.test, lty = 2)
qqline(std_resid.test)

Reduced range of predicted values

In order to provide a proper range of application for the linear regression model, we re-plot the residuals only for predicted sale prices below 300k$.

ggplot(mapping = aes(x = exp(pred.test.BMA$fit) , y = pred.test.BMA.resid )) + geom_point() + xlim(50000, 300000) + ylim(-100000, 100000) + geom_smooth(method='lm') + labs(x = 'Predictions under BMA', y = 'Residuals')

As can be seen, in this range the residuals are more evenly spread around the zero mean value. We can also plot their quantile-quantile distribution, compared with the theoretical normal distribution.

res <- dplyr::filter(as.data.frame(pred.test.BMA.resid), exp(pred.test.BMA$fit) < 300000 )

# Normalize residuals
mu_resid <- mean(res$pred.test.BMA.resid)
sd_resid <- sd(res$pred.test.BMA.resid)
std_resid.test <- (res$pred.test.BMA.resid - mu_resid)/sd_resid

# Normal Q-Q plot
qqnorm(std_resid.test, lty = 2)
qqline(std_resid.test)

In this range of values, the residuals are much closer to a normal distribution.

Section 4.2 Final Model RMSE

The RMSE of the final model has been calculated in Section 3.5 and has a value of 24455.5$. This is better than the one obtained with the initial simplified linear regression model.

Section 4.3 Final Model Evaluation

As a final test, we calculate the coverage probability of the BMA model using the ames_test database.

# Get dataset of predictions and confidence intervals
out = as.data.frame(cbind(exp(confint(pred.test.BMA)),
                          price = ames_test$price))

# Fix names in dataset
colnames(out)[1:2] <- c("lwr", "upr")  #fix names

# Get Coverage
pred.test.BMA.coverage <- out %>% summarize(cover = sum(price >= lwr & price <= upr)/n())
pred.test.BMA.coverage
##       cover
## 1 0.9461444

This value is fairly close to \(95\%\), as expected. The main drawback of the final model is that it tends to underpredict the price of the most expensive houses, as shown by the analysis of the residuals.

Section 4.4 Final Model Validation

For the validation of the final linear regression model we use a third independent data set, from which once again we select only the houses sold in Normal conditions.

load("ames_validation.Rdata")
ames_validation <- ames_validation %>%
  filter(Sale.Condition == "Normal")

First, we predict the log(price) from the ames_validation data set using the BMA model.

# Predict log(price) on validation database
pred.valid.BMA <- predict(model.bas, newdata = ames_validation, estimator="BMA", prediction=TRUE, se.fit=TRUE)

Then, we proceed to checking the RMSE, which is expressed in Dollars.

# Calculate RMSE
pred.valid.BMA.rmse <- sqrt(mean((exp(pred.valid.BMA$fit) - ames_validation$price)^2))
pred.valid.BMA.rmse
## [1] 21738.66

In this case, the RMSE is noticeably lower than with the ames_test database, suggesting that the performance of this model is subject to a certain degree of variability. Finally, we calculate the coverage probability on the ames_validation database.

# Calculate coverage
out = as.data.frame(cbind(exp(confint(pred.valid.BMA)),
                          price = ames_validation$price))

colnames(out)[1:2] <- c("lwr", "upr")  #fix names

pred.valid.BMA.coverage <- out %>% summarize(cover = sum(price >= lwr & price <= upr)/n())
pred.valid.BMA.coverage
##       cover
## 1 0.9554391

The percentage of the 95% predicted credible intervals that contain the true price of the house in the validation data set is again close to \(95\%\).

Finally, we will try to answer the original question of this study: where are most of the overvalued and undervalued houses located? Overvalued properties will have a negative residual, whereas undervalued properties will have positive residuals. Let us calculate the average residuals grouped by neighborhood.

pred.valid.BMA.resid <- exp(pred.valid.BMA$fit) - ames_validation$price
out <- cbind.data.frame(res = pred.valid.BMA.resid,
                          neigh = ames_validation$Neighborhood)
grouped_mean_res <- out %>% group_by(neigh) %>% summarize(m = mean(res))

The following neighborhood contains, on average, most of the overvalued properties:

grouped_mean_res[which.min(grouped_mean_res$m),1]
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   neigh  
##   <fct>  
## 1 NoRidge

On the contrary, most of the undervalued properties can be found, on average, in the following neighborhood:

grouped_mean_res[which.max(grouped_mean_res$m),1]
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   neigh  
##   <fct>  
## 1 SawyerW

This is then the neighborhood in which good investments can be made.

Part 5 - Conclusion

It has been shown that the Bayesian Adaptive Sampling method can efficiently generate a linear model of the price of houses in Ames, Iowa given the current dataset. In order to obtain this result, it has been necessary to eliminate most of the potential outliers, i.e. the houses sold in conditions other than normal, and to transform the price and area variables by taking their natural logarithm. At the end of this study, the most important question is: what determines the price of the most expensive houses? It may be that there is some key variable that plays a role only above a certain threshold of price, which has not been included in the present model. This will certainly require further investigation.
